        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12816",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Another thought:  \n\nAre class variables saved when the object is serialized?\nOne of the proposals we've had is to allow rows and rowsets to be serialized.\nMaybe this is a good reason to keep $_cols as an instance variable.\n\nOn the other hand, perhaps the metadata cache should *not* be serialized, because we're reasonably certain that the cache expiration threshold would have passed by the time we unserialize the row\/rowset.  So should we always refresh the metadata information when we unserialize?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-16T17:19:26.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-16T17:19:26.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/13742",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Implementation ideas:\n\n- In Zend_Db_Table_Abstract, add a class variable $_metadataCache, which is of type Zend_Cache_Core.  This is initialized to null in the class definition.  The cache can be set with a setMetadataCache() method, or the 'metadataCache' element of the options array in the constructor.  Setting this in the class definition is not supported.\n- In Zend_Db_Table_Abstract::_setupMetadata(), before calling describeTable(), check if the $_metadataCache is non-null and contains a key corresponding to the table (use the physical SQL table name for this).  If so, and the cache entry is not expired, use that cache entry to populate the class variable $_metadata, instead of calling describeTable().\n- The content to store in the cache entry is simply the array of information returned by describeTable().  Everyone else ($_table, $_primary, etc.) is inexpensive to reconstruct in the Table class, since it does not require a round-trip to the RDBMS.\n- If we did call describeTable(), and the $_metadataCache is set to a non-null object, save the metadata in the cache, under a key corresponding to the table.\n- Also support a default cache.  Like the default database adapter that is set as a static property of the Zend_Db_Table_Abstract class, the default cache serves as a default object, so if the table's $_metadataCache object is null, also check the abstract class's $_defaultMetadataCache static property, and use that.  So the abstract class needs static methods setDefaultMetadataCache() and getDefaultMetadataCache().",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=bkarwin",
                        "name": "bkarwin",
                        "displayName": "Bill Karwin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-03-27T14:48:03.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-03-27T14:48:03.000+0000"
